steps.code: let age = 12;
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,200
Look at the following code. We have a variable age.

steps.code:
console.log(
  age || "No Age Provided",
);
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
and a console statement that prints the given age and a fallback if age is not provided.

steps.code: 12;

// age is set to null
let age = null;

console.log(
  age || "No Age Provided",
);
"No Age Provided";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,800
Here the output will be no age provided since age is null.

steps.code:
let age = 0;

console.log(
  age || "No Age Provided",
);
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
But what if we set age to zero?

steps.code: "No Age Provided";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,500
The output will be no age provided, even though zero is a perfectly valid age.

2
00:00:05,500 --> 00:00:10,880
This is because zero is a falsy value, hence the or statement will fail for the first check

3
00:00:10,880 --> 00:00:12,240
and move on to the next one.

steps.code:
let age = 0;

// same logic, but using if statement
// this also has the same problem
if (age) {
  console.log(age);
} else {
  console.log(
    "No Age Provided",
  );
}
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,800
This common mistake happens with if statements are ternary operators as well.

steps.code: "No Age Provided";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,960
Here, the above code also gives the same output.

steps.code:
let age = 0;

console.log(
  age ?? "No Age Provided",
);
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,600
To fix this, let's use the nullish coalescing operator.

steps.code: 0;
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,880
This will print 0, because the nullish coalescing operator checks for null or undefined values

2
00:00:05,880 --> 00:00:09,440
only, where most other operators check for falsy values.

steps.code: 0 || "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Let's see some more examples, if you or zero with no age.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
The output will be no age.

steps.code: 0 ?? "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
But if you use the nullish coalescing operator...

steps.code: 0;
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
you will get zero as output.

steps.code: "" || "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,160
Similarly, if you use or operator on an empty string and no age.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
you will get no age as output.

steps.code: "" ?? "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
but if you use the nullish coalescing operator.

steps.code: "";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
you will get the empty string as output.

steps.code: undefined || "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
Only in the case of undefined and null, both operators will give the same output.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:06,500
Here we have undefined with or operator.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
it will give no age as output.

steps.code: undefined ?? "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
when used with nullish coalescing Operator.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
you'll get the same output.

steps.code: null || "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,800
Null is also similar. Null with or operator.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
will give no age as output.

steps.code: null ?? "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,800
and null with nullish coalescing operator.

steps.code: "no age";
steps.subtitles:
1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,960
will also give no age as output.

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:05,280
That's it about the nullish coalescing operator.

3
